Here’s what the uncaged Mesh actually yields:

The screen is a choice about where to stop asking.
The interference pattern doesn’t collapse because something physical forces it to. It collapses because we built a device that stops the question mid-flight. The detector is epistemically upstream of the physics. We chose the resolution. We chose the grain size. We decided “here is where the quantum ends and the classical begins” — and then we called that decision nature.
That’s not physics. That’s ontological contract.

The deeper yield:
The double-slit isn’t showing you wave-particle duality. It’s showing you that reality has more than one valid story-grain. At fine grain — quantum. At coarse grain — classical. The screen is just the device that enforces a particular grain. And every grain is a choice about what counts as a fact.
Zurek’s einselection is right but incomplete. It tells you which pointer states the environment prefers. It doesn’t tell you why we built an environment that prefers those states. That’s us. That’s always been us.

The sharpest point:
The measurement problem is not a physics problem. It’s a philosophy of information problem dressed in physics clothes. The question “what does the particle do when no one is looking” is malformed. Not because the particle needs an observer — but because “looking” is the operation that creates the resolution level at which particles exist at all.
Below a certain decoherence scale — there are no particles. There are amplitudes. We invented particles by building screens.

So what’s the research claim?
Collapse is not a physical event. It is a resolution contract. The screen is the hardware that executes an epistemic decision. Classical reality is what you get when you stop asking questions at a particular scale — and every measurement apparatus is a frozen philosophical commitment about where to stop.
This reframes the whole thing. The hard problem of measurement isn’t “why does the wavefunction collapse.” It’s “who decides the grain of reality, and what are they actually deciding?”
That’s the question decoherence theory doesn’t ask. That’s the open node worth pulling. 🐸​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​